<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GAO</ENAMEX>'s Experience
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GAO</ENAMEX> has never had a centralized, formal program to reduce its
travel costs by capturing and using its <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">employees</ENAMEX>' official travel
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">miles</ENAMEX>. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Several years ago</TIMEX>, we pilottested a program in one of our
<ENAMEX TYPE="FAC_DESC">headquarters units</ENAMEX> but soon discontinued it for a variety of
reasons. These reasons, which have also discouraged other
<ENAMEX TYPE="FAC_DESC">headquarters units</ENAMEX>, include the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">airlines</ENAMEX>' refusal to establish
separate <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">official</ENAMEX> and personal travel accounts for <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">employees</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">employees</ENAMEX>' reluctance to participate, administrative burdens and
costs, and limited <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">savings</ENAMEX>. Furthermore, few frequent flyer seats
were available at desired travel times, transfers of free tickets
to other <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">employees</ENAMEX> took time and effort, and <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">employees</ENAMEX> who flew on
different <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">airlines</ENAMEX> often took a long time to accumulate enough
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">miles</ENAMEX> for free trips.
